Doom

Currently the most-polished app for playing Doom on Android devices. I was a previous user of D-Touch, an older version of this app, but this version is newer and updated. It has a very good touch controls scheme that's easy to use, and if you don't want to use touch controls, controller support is excellent with universal mapping across all four source ports.  This app includes four source ports, including the current (as of this writing) version of Chocolate Doom and a recent build of GZDoom for use with most mods. What's awesome is that I can playback Doom demos on the go while using only a fraction of my mobile data; instead of streaming video, I can watch Doom demos played natively through a Doom source port. Also, multiplayer in Chocolate Doom works great.  Compatibility and performance is great. Although I would recommend a port of the Eternity Engine source port over Doom Retro; not that Doom Retro is a bad source port, but the Eternity Engine would be great to have on Android for its features and demo compatibility. Also, compatibility with Android 3.1 Honeycomb would be good, since the old version of this app was compatible.  Otherwise, I would highly recommend this app.

Some tips: Reduce touch 'Up/Down Sensitivity' to 0 so there is no vertical look. Reduce general touch sensitivity. Enable 'Gyro' aim assist controls.

THE best Doom source port for Android. Stable, runs smooth, has gamepad support, and a solid choice of ports:  *GZDoom, the most advanced Doom source port, runs popular mods like Brutal Doom and Demonsteele. Supports all the main IWADS ((Free)Doom, Heretic, Hexen, Strife, Chex Quest), and many standalone games too (Action Doom 2, Rise of the Wool Ball, Adventures of Square, and more).  *Chocolate Doom, a nearly 1:1 recreation of the original .EXEs, with support for the "big four" Doom engine games ((Free)Doom, Heretic, Hexen, Strife), and the best multiplayer support of the bunch.  *Doom Retro, a fork of Chocolate Doom which stays true to classic Doom gameplay while adding nice cosmetic features such as blood color correction, random decoration more blood, etc.  *PrBoom+, a very popular vanilla-compatible port which supports advanced "Boom" mapping features, comes with some basic graphics upgrades (high-resolution, uncapped FPS) while remaining true to vanilla gameplay.  Whether you're a Doom purist or like new, fancy mods, this is a solid choice. If you don't feel like paying, there's Freedoom, but it runs on only an older GZDoom. But this one is the best Doom port.

Someone finally did it. The ultimate portable version of Doom with support 
for modern sourceports. You can play everything from the first homebrew wad 
ever made to Cacowards 2017 entries. It even supports Heretic, Hexen, and 
Strife, in case you want varying levels of RPG-i-ness with your pistol 
start. Customizable touch controls and an amazing weapon wheel solution for 
swapping to the weapon you want when you want it. Really fantastic work, 
and considering the monumental library of original content for Doom, this 
is easily the best value on the Android platform.

Before anyone out there flags this as a copyright infringement... do your 
homework! Id software made the source code for Doom open source in the late 
90s... the only thing not open source (aside from some copyrighted sound 
code which the Doom community quickly replaced) was the assets inside the 
.wad file... which IS NOT INCLUDED! As for this port... very solid design. 
Controls are a little wonky (it is afterall adapting touch buttons for what 
used to be controlled by a mouse) and may need some personalization to your 
tastes... but is highly configurable. Few devs give you the option of 
adjusting the placement of virtual buttons.

content: Delta Touch is the great successor to D-Touch, returning with the latest versions of the three source ports plus the new Doom Retro.  For anyone unfamiliar with D-Touch, this allows you to play Doom on the go. From the near-vanilla Chocolate Doom to the very moddable GZDoom, there's a port in here you'll like.  Touch screen controls are usually clunky but Open Touch did better than the average mobile port's controls, with fully customizable button layout and two analog sticks that follow your fingers. It also has gamepad support for anyone who wants a bit more control.  I totally recommend buying this if you have a somewhat powerful device to take Doom (and other mods/TCs) on the go.
